{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17601015","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17601015"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:09:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:09:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15642"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15642","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15642"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.35,0.35,0.09,0.13,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8333"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71022"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8333","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8333"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15642"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56493"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"840"},{"type":"tags","id":"2994"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5295"},{"type":"tags","id":"7010"},{"type":"tags","id":"10111"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20101"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20102"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71022","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71022"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents with eight months of progressive central obesity, facial plethora, and easy bruising. Laboratory results show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EMorning cortisol: 850 nmol/L (140-690)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EACTH: \u003C1 pmol/L (2-11)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Adrenal adenoma","Cushing disease","Ectopic ACTH syndrome","Bilateral adrenal hyperplasia","Factitious Cushing syndrome"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has features of Cushing syndrome with suppressed ACTH levels, indicating an \u003Cstrong\u003Eadrenal adenoma\u003C/strong\u003E as the likely cause. Adrenal tumours autonomously produce cortisol, suppressing pituitary ACTH production through negative feedback.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECushing disease\u003C/strong\u003E (pituitary ACTH-producing adenoma) would show elevated ACTH levels\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEctopic ACTH syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E would show markedly elevated ACTH levels\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBilateral adrenal hyperplasia\u003C/strong\u003E is typically ACTH-dependent\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFactitious Cushing syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E from exogenous glucocorticoids would show suppressed cortisol and ACTH\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe combination of high cortisol with suppressed ACTH strongly suggests an autonomous adrenal source of cortisol production.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Adrenal adenomas autonomously produce cortisol, leading to suppressed ACTH levels.","ACTH levels help distinguish between pituitary-dependent and adrenal causes of Cushing syndrome.","Primary adrenal causes of Cushing syndrome include adenomas, carcinomas, and bilateral hyperplasia."],"references":["Melmed, S., Polonsky, K. S., Larsen, P. R., \u0026 Kronenberg, H. M. (2015). Williams textbook of endocrinology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Clark, O. H., Duh, Q. Y., Kebebew, E., Gosnell, J. E., \u0026 Shen, W. T. (Eds.). (2016). Textbook of endocrine surgery. JP Medical Ltd","Young, W. F. (2011). Netter\u0027s Endocrine System: Netter Collection of Medical Illustrations: Endocrine System E-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Wass, J. A., \u0026 Stewart, P. M. (Eds.). (2011). Oxford textbook of endocrinology and diabetes. Oxford University Press, USA","Allen MJ, Sharma S. Physiology, Adrenocorticotropic Hormone (ACTH) [Updated 2023 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK500031/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56493"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15642"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56493","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56493"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-16T18:57:34+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-16T18:59:08+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8333"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71022"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior,